  "chunk_index": 7,
  "summary": "Bondel recounts the accident to Dr. Castle, explaining that she believed she had nearly run over a man walking unsteadily near a roadside gate. However, Dr. Castle reveals that the man was not hit by the car but had actually been shot with a rifle bullet, causing fatal internal bleeding. Before dying, the man had mentioned a \"seven o'clock clock.\" Dr. Castle suggests the shooter may have been an accidental bystander or someone who did not realize they had hit a person.\n\nBondel and Dr. Castle proceed to the police station, where an officer dismisses the shooting as the work of local troublemakers practicing target shooting. Bondel identifies the deceased as Ronny DeVille from Albany after finding a business card on his body. This discovery causes Bondel significant distress; she recognizes DeVille as a friend of Bill from the State Department and links his death to the previous death of Gerry Wade. She also connects the \"seven-faced clock\" mentioned by DeVille to a detail in Gerry Wade's final letter to his sister.\n\nBondel returns home to inform her father, Lord Kettlemere, of the situation. During their conversation, she asks him about the \"seven-faced clock\" and a man named Jimmy Sycamore. Lord Kettlemere initially appears distracted but eventually recalls that George Lomax, a Cabinet Minister and the Queen's personal assistant for foreign affairs, received a threatening letter. Lomax claimed the threat originated from the \"seven-faced clock\" and intended to report the matter to Scotland Yard.",
